## Rules / Never do
- Read CLAUDE.md, DECISIONS.md, and SESSIONS.md at the start of every session and stay anchored to them (this is enforced by a SessionStart hook — see `.claude/settings.json` — but state it here too as the source of truth)
- Verify external claims (API behavior, docs, third-party task briefs) against live/actual behavior before trusting them and writing code against them — a docs page or a brief being plausible is not the same as it being correct right now
- Use plan mode (or otherwise get explicit sign-off) before non-trivial implementation work — multiple valid approaches, multi-file changes, or unclear requirements all qualify
- Commit only when explicitly asked; never use destructive git operations (force-push, hard reset, history rewrites) without explicit confirmation
- Always read a file before editing it; if an exact-match replacement fails, re-read the file to find the actual current content rather than reaching for a regex fallback
- Proactively suggest a checkpoint when EITHER (a) the session has covered several unrelated subtasks or run long, OR (b) the working directory has changed to a genuinely different project than where the session started (e.g. you began in project A, then `cd`'d into unrelated project B and kept working). Trigger (b) is a stronger, more specific signal than (a) and should not wait for (a) to also be true — a conversation that has drifted across multiple unrelated project directories is exactly when stale/cross-project context bleed is most likely, and each project's docs should be checkpointed before moving on. To checkpoint: update SESSIONS.md (and memory, if available) with current state, then suggest the user consider `/clear` before continuing — don't wait to be asked. A fresh session re-anchors on CLAUDE.md/DECISIONS.md/SESSIONS.md via the SessionStart hook rather than accumulated conversational drift, which is the actual mechanism that keeps long-running work reliable — not a fixed context-percentage target.
